---
const facts = ['5 layers', '3 control surfaces', 'Private by default'];

const layers = [
  ['Physical + network', 'Connectivity, power, and private reachability.'],
  ['Compute', 'Separate daily workstation from always-on workers and service hosts.'],
  ['Control plane', 'Git, Ansible, just, and encrypted secrets keep the environment reproducible.'],
  ['Services', 'Forge, search, state, monitoring, notifications, and Hub.'],
  ['Agent layer', 'Interactive sessions, dispatch, review, and lightweight coordination.'],
];

const surfaces = [
  ['Interactive', 'Shape, inspect, debug, and decide in real time.'],
  ['Dispatch', 'Run bounded background work in isolated sandboxes.'],
  ['Review', 'Return through PRs, artifacts, dashboards, and notifications.'],
];

const sequence = ['Shape work', 'Dispatch', 'Isolated run', 'Artifact or PR', 'Review'];
---

<div class="essay-page architecture-page">
  <section class="page-hero-note-grid">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">System</p>
      <h1 class="page-display-title">How GalexC is arranged</h1>
      <p class="page-lede">
        GalexC is a personal AI operating environment built in layers. Under the
        surface are private networking, boring compute, a reproducible control plane,
        and a small set of durable services. On top sits the agent layer: interactive
        sessions for shaping work, dispatch for bounded execution, and review surfaces
        that keep the human clearly in charge.
      </p>
    </div>
    <ul class="page-note-list">
      {facts.map((fact) => <li>{fact}</li>)}
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="page-module page-module-panel architecture-plate">
    <p class="eyebrow">System at a glance</p>
    <div class="architecture-bands">
      {
        layers.map(([title, body], index) => (
          <div class:list={['architecture-band', index === layers.length - 1 && 'architecture-band-active']}>
            <p class="architecture-band__title">{title}</p>
            <p>{body}</p>
          </div>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-grid-three">
    {
      surfaces.map(([title, body]) => (
        <article class="page-module page-module-panel surface-card">
          <p class="eyebrow">Control surface</p>
          <h2>{title}</h2>
          <p>{body}</p>
        </article>
      ))
    }
  </section>

  <section class="page-module">
    <div class="module-heading-row">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">One unit of work</p>
        <h2 class="page-section-title">A bounded path back to review</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="page-caption">The blue path is execution. The rest of the system exists to support it.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="workflow-ribbon">
      {
        sequence.map((step, index) => (
          <>
            <div class="workflow-ribbon__step">{step}</div>
            {index < sequence.length - 1 && <div class="workflow-ribbon__connector" aria-hidden="true"></div>}
          </>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-grid-two">
    <article class="page-module">
      <p class="eyebrow">Why the boundaries are strict</p>
      <p>
        The stack is arranged around containment as much as capability. Services are
        private by default. Containers keep hosts boring and replaceable. Search reduces
        blind wandering. Worktree isolation, allowlists, and review surfaces keep agent
        work narrow and inspectable.
      </p>
    </article>
    <aside class="page-module page-module-panel legend-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Legend</p>
      <ul class="legend-card__list">
        <li><strong>Blue path</strong> - active work moving from shaping to review</li>
        <li><strong>Paper bands</strong> - durable layers of the system</li>
        <li><strong>Dotted links</strong> - search, control, and coordination</li>
      </ul>
    </aside>
  </section>
</div>
